post_text: Help fund our new class! Good morning City High Community! The school year is upon us and we're offering a new art class, "Art in Our Community" a comprehensive course focused on the art and artists of Tucson, Arizona and the surrounding areas. This course includes interactive activities and studio projects representing a wide variety of artists and cultures in our community, artistic styles, and media. Students will meet (virtually or when it's safe) and experience the work of local artists from a variety of backgrounds, visit and explore artist communities (when it's safe), and learn about local business that promote and support the arts. This course will give students the opportunity to review works of art from various artists, styles, and cultural groups that celebrates cultural diversity and an understanding of global views within our local Tucson community. BUT we need stuff do these things. If you are able, please make a tax deductible donation to help fund this new class and this great opportunity for our City High students during these difficult times!

post_text: Good morning City High Community! I have some great news! Thanks to a handful of generous donors, each art student at City will be equipped with their own professional quality supplies, including paper, graphite, charcoal, white charcoal, pens, erasers, sharpeners, blending stumps, sandpaper, drawing boards, colored pencils, and ALL THE THINGS YOU’LL NEED for art this year to start remotely! City High knows how important it is for each student to have equal access to quality materials, and this pandemic poses a real challenge, but we’ll power through! So much gratitude to the folks who helped make this possible! We miss you guys but we’ll get through it and be together soon! Stay safe!

City High School (Tucson, AZ) added 117 new photos from May — at City High School (Tucson, AZ).
June 12 at 3:12 PM · Tucson, AZ ·

It's been a difficult year for the class of 2020!
School: canceled
Prom: canceled
Graduation: canceled... sort of.
City High teachers and staff came up with a solution to keep everyone safe and still have a graduation that honors each family by bringing the ceremony to them, caravan style!
Each student received a gift card to a local restaurant or grocery store of their choice (Boca Tacos, Poco & Mom's, Bianchi's, Safeway), a "Stay Home Class of 2020" t shirt that was designed (Ashley Loberg) and printed (Gabacho Media) locally with proceeds going to Tucson Helping Tucson, a personalized cake from a local bakery (Nadine's), and a curbside, socially distant visit from the graduation bus a caravan of friends, family and neighbors they chose to invite.
After 4 days and over 300 miles, the City High teachers and staff were exhausted, but so grateful to be able to honor our 2020 grads. City High would not be the wonderful community that it is without our students and families!
Congratulations Class of 2020!

post_text:
Dear City High Students & Families,

It is with a heavy heart that I tell you the news that I will not be returning to teach at City High next fall. After 15 years of teaching, I decided it was time to take a break.

Please know that I have thoroughly enjoyed working with all of our hard-working and creative students over the years, collaborating with the best colleagues there are, and have really appreciated all the support from our families. Thank you. I will miss you all.

There is some uncertainty about what is next for me (like many these days). I will continue to work from home for most of June, completing my grant reporting obligations and tying up some other loose ends. I have been working closely with school leadership & our hiring teams to ensure that my drama program, guitar students, VOICES program coordination, and advisory will all be in good hands going forward.

Please feel free to reach out if you want to stay in touch. I will continue using my cityccl.org email through June.

Much love to everyone,
Tom
text:

Please know that I have thoroughly enjoyed working with all of our hard-working and creative students over the years, collaborating with the best colleagues there are, and have really appreciated all the support from our families. Thank you. I will miss you all.

There is some uncertainty about what is next for me (like many these days). I will continue to work from home for most of June, completing my grant reporting obligations and tying up some other loose ends. I have been working closely with school leadership & our hiring teams to ensure that my drama program, guitar students, VOICES program coordination, and advisory will all be in good hands going forward.

Please feel free to reach out if you want to stay in touch. I will continue using my cityccl.org email through June.

Much love to everyone,
Tom

post_text: Can you believe it’s been 3...4... um... weeks, no wait...what day is it? 🤔🤔🤔 Anyway, just because we aren’t in school doesn’t mean City High kids aren’t working. Check out this fancy fun cake Fran turned in as their art project last week! Staying home might mean that you can’t get your hands on expensive colored pencils or huge paper but that doesn’t mean you can’t get creative and learn something new or get better at something you already love. Now is the time to work on yourself and learn about what you can offer to the world when this is all over. Take advantage of this time and show us what you‘ve got!

post_text: Congratulations to Andrea, Lesay, and Colter!
shared_text:
Arts Foundation for Tucson and Southern Arizona
April 21 at 3:01 PM ·

Congratulations to the 2020 class of the
Pima County Youth Arts Scholarship!

Congratulations to the 8 students who will be receiving a $2,140 scholarship toward enrollment at Pima Community College or Tohono O’odham Community College. The Youth Arts Scholarship is designed to identify and reward high school seniors within Pima County who demonstrate excellence in dance, music, theater, visual arts, media arts, or literary arts.

Andrea Lopez, City High School, Visual Arts
Lesay Lopez , Project MORE High School, Visual Arts
Colter Pauley, City High School, Visual Arts
Emmanuelle Alvarez Romo, Sunnyside High School, Music
Olivia Rosenberg , Sky Islands High School, Visual Arts
Miette Stewart, Tucson Magnet High School, Film/Video
Carlos Sanchez, Sunnyside High School, Visual Arts
Sofia Urcadez, Desert View High School, Poetry

This scholarship is supported by individual contributions as well as a $10,000 donation from local artist Janey Katz.

(Image: From top left: Carlos Sanchez; Andrea Lopez; Colter Pauley; Lesay Lopez; Olivia Rosenberg)

post_text:
City High Radio took home 8 awards at the Arizona Interscholastic Press Association Fall Journalism Conference:

Best Broadcasting--First Place ("Superior") for overall excellence in broadcasting in TV/Film/Radio for our podcast "City High Radio"

Best Podcast--First Place ("Superior") for our podcast "City High Radio"

Geronimo Sanchez--First Place ("Superior") in the Radio/TV/Film Feature category for the story "What Is Your Greatest Fear?"

Geronimo Sanchez-- Second Place ("Excellence") in the Radio/TV/Film Commentary category for the story "Living Dangerously"

Duri Kim--Honorable Mention in the Radio/TV/Film Commentary category for the story "What Holds You Back In Life"

Paloma Martinez--First Place ("Superior") in the Radio/TV/Film Commentary category for the story "I Haven't Given Up on Christmas Yet"

Paloma Martinez--Honorable Mention in the Radio/TV/Film Feature category for the story "A Crisis In the Desert."

Samantha Zazueta--Second Place ("Excellence") in the Radio/TV/Film Feature category for the story "My Incarcerated Family."

post_text:
We are excited to announce that Tucson's current poet laureate, TC Tolbert, will be returning to City High School's GSA next month to host a free 3-week series of poetry workshops. You don't have to be a current participant in our GSA to come!

The series runs during our GSA meetings, 3:15-4:15 in room 103 on the following days:Monday, 11/4, Wednesday, 11/13,
and Monday, 11/18.

Check out the website here: https://www.tucsontnbqpoetry.com/
